Citations
Date: 14/10/1933
Source: Press, The
Author:
Vol / Page: 15
Edition:
Quote:  (Acland Gloss.) Eye-clip: To cut the wool away from round a sheep's eyes. If this is not done, the wool, especially on merinos is apt to grow over the  and make the sheep wool-blind. Some people speak of eye-clipping  as Winking. (G.P.W.; C.)
Notes:

Date: 16/10/1950
Source: NZ Journal of Agriculture
Author:
Vol / Page: 349
Edition:
Quote: Lambs ... while ewes are being shorn ... are being wigged or eye-clipped ... Through eye clipping, wool blindness is avoided; a wool-blind sheep is seriously hampered on run country in its search for feed and consequently does not thrive.
